			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: upgrade suggestion<a name="36950"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 28 04 9:32 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">your intelligence is in the toilet...might look to boosting it in a strategic manner. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Well, he doesn't have fade and unless he's into heavy swarm kiting, a 2k manapool should be more than enough. 
<br />

<br />
Not only is LDoN good for gear upgrades via adventure points, the random augs that drop are great to shore up stats that you find to be lacking. For example, 4-5 Int augs would give a sizable manapool boost for zero cost.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Most plate classes opt for the Takish armor (Royal Attendant) but unless you're heavily into LDoN, a better option may be the Malevolent _ of Suffering armor from Miragul.
<br />

<br />
A quick comparison:
<br />

<br />
Royal Attendant Greaves of Sand vs Malevolent Greaves of Suffering 
<br />

<br />
+4 AC
<br />
+2 STR
<br />
-6 CHA
<br />
+1 INT/WIS
<br />
+10 AGI
<br />
+15 HP/Mana
<br />
And the resists are a coin toss FR/DR vs CR/MR
<br />
Both have identical aug slots (1/2/3).
<br />

<br />
The Royal Attendant costs 1492 points whereas the Malevolent costs 760.
<br />

<br />
At this point you have to ask yourself does 730 Advent points (14+ Normal adventures at lvl 65 or a minimum of 11 hours) justify the marginal increase in stats? Would upgrading 2 pieces of your gear to Malevolent be a better overall improvement than purchasing 1 piece of Royal Attendant?
<br />
Conversely, you could opt to aug out the Malevolent armor that you get with Mana Regen augs, HP/Mana augs or any other stats that you feel need improvement.
<br />

<br />
I guess it depends on your playstyle and how much you really like LDoN.
<br />
Each piece of Royal Attendant (without augs) will take a minimum of 23 hours played... assuming you have minimal travel/wait time and finish each adventure in minimum time.
<br />
For a player who does strictly Hard adventures, the time could be lowered to about 16 hours.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
